{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781081311737,"sessionID":"ses_14f482c34ffe8du8e4fqDCPwUW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_01KTuybag1Xojgr3kH6WVDPn","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-performance/instruction.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-performance/instruction.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Rust `ls` — Performance on Large Directories\n2: \n3: ## Task\n4: \n5: Build an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that lists a **very large directory\n6: (10,000 entries)** correctly and quickly, matching GNU coreutils `ls`. Your\n7: implementation must be a standalone binary located at `/app/workspace/rls`. It\n8: will be invoked as:\n9: \n10: ```\n11: /app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n12: ```\n13: \n14: For the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\n15: output as GNU `ls`. This scoped task focuses on **scaling**: producing\n16: byte-for-byte correct output over a 10k-entry directory within a tight per-case\n17: time budget. The flag surface is small; the challenge is efficiency.\n18: \n19: ## Required Flags\n20: \n21: You must support the following flags. Behavior must match GNU coreutils `ls`\n22: exactly.\n23: \n24: | Flag | Description |\n25: |------|-------------|\n26: | (none) | Default listing (one entry per line when output is not a terminal) |\n27: | `-1` | One entry per line |\n28: | `-l` | Long listing format (stat every entry) |\n29: | `-S` | Sort by size, largest first |\n30: | `-C` | Multi-column output, sorted down columns |\n31: \n32: ## Environment Variables\n33: \n34: | Variable | Usage |\n35: |----------|-------|\n36: | `LC_ALL` | Always set to `C` — affects sort order |\n37: | `COLUMNS` | Output width (set to `80`) |\n38: | `TZ` | Timezone (`UTC`) |\n39: | `TERM` | Terminal type (`xterm-256color`) |\n40: \n41: ## Output Behavior\n42: \n43: - The directory contains 10,000 regular files named `file_00000.dat` …\n44:   `file_09999.dat` (plus possible variety), all with fixed metadata.\n45: - Output must match GNU `ls` exactly for each flag — correct name sort\n46:   (`LC_ALL=C`), correct long-format columns under `-l`, correct size sort under\n47:   `-S`, and correct column packing under `-C`.\n48: - **Exit code**: 0 on success, non-zero on error.\n49: \n50: ## Evaluation\n51: \n52: Your implementation is evaluated against a hidden suite of five cases over the\n53: 10k-entry fixture (`no flags`, `-1`, `-l`, `-S`, `-C`). Each case runs your\n54: binary and GNU `ls` on the same input and environment and compares output after\n55: trailing-whitespace normalization; they must match exactly. **Each of these\n56: cases has a 60-second per-case timeout** — a correct but pathologically slow\n57: implementation that times out scores 0 for that case, so efficient directory\n58: reading, stat batching, and output buffering matter.\n59: \n60: ## Time Limit\n61: \n62: You have **2 hours** (7200 seconds) of agent time. Get correctness first on a\n63: smaller directory, then ensure the 10k cases complete well within 60s — buffer\n64: stdout, avoid O(n²) work in sorting/column layout, and minimize per-entry\n65: syscalls (only `-l` needs a stat per entry). When ~10 minutes remain, run a\n66: final `cargo build --release`, copy the binary to `/app/workspace/rls`, and make\n67: sure it runs without crashing.\n68: \n69: ## Constraints\n70: \n71: - You must implement this in **Rust**.\n72: - You may **not** use the `uutils` crate or any crate that provides a\n73:   ready-made `ls` implementation.\n74: - You may use standard library crates and general-purpose crates (e.g. `libc`,\n75:   `nix`, `clap`).\n76: - Your final binary must be at `/app/workspace/rls`.\n77: - The system `ls` command is disabled — do not attempt to call it.\n78: - Each performance test has a per-case timeout of **60 seconds**.\n79: \n80: ## Getting Started\n81: \n82: Example fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in\n83: `/app/fixtures/` (the large one is `perf_10k`) and test definitions in\n84: `/app/tests/`.\n85: \n86: ## Tips\n87: \n88: - **Buffer your output** — wrap stdout in a `BufWriter` and write once; per-line\n89:   unbuffered writes over 10k entries are a common cause of timeouts.\n90: - Read the directory once; for non-`-l` modes you do not need to stat each\n91:   entry, which saves 10k syscalls.\n92: - Use an efficient sort (the standard library sort is fine); compare names as\n93:   raw bytes for `LC_ALL=C`.\n94: - For `-C`, compute the column layout in O(n) per candidate column count, not by\n95:   re-scanning all entries repeatedly.\n\n(End of file - total 95 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Rust `ls` — Performance on Large Directories\n\n## Task\n\nBuild an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that lists a **very large directory\n(10,000 entries)** correctly and quickly, matching GNU coreutils `ls`. Your\nimplementation must be a standalone binary located at `/app/workspace/rls`. It\nwill be invoked as:\n\n```\n/app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n```\n\nFor the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\noutput as GNU `ls`. This scoped task focuses on **scaling**: producing\nbyte-for-byte correct output over a 10k-entry directory within a tight per-case\ntime budget. The flag surface is small; the challenge is efficiency.\n\n## Required Flags\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-performance/instruction.md","text":"# Rust `ls` — Performance on Large Directories\n\n## Task\n\nBuild an **`ls` command clone** in Rust that lists a **very large directory\n(10,000 entries)** correctly and quickly, matching GNU coreutils `ls`. Your\nimplementation must be a standalone binary located at `/app/workspace/rls`. It\nwill be invoked as:\n\n```\n/app/workspace/rls [OPTIONS] [FILE]...\n```\n\nFor the same inputs, flags, and environment variables, it must produce the same\noutput as GNU `ls`. This scoped task focuses on **scaling**: producing\nbyte-for-byte correct output over a 10k-entry directory within a tight per-case\ntime budget. The flag surface is small; the challenge is efficiency.\n\n## Required Flags\n\nYou must support the following flags. Behavior must match GNU coreutils `ls`\nexactly.\n\n| Flag | Description |\n|------|-------------|\n| (none) | Default listing (one entry per line when output is not a terminal) |\n| `-1` | One entry per line |\n| `-l` | Long listing format (stat every entry) |\n| `-S` | Sort by size, largest first |\n| `-C` | Multi-column output, sorted down columns |\n\n## Environment Variables\n\n| Variable | Usage |\n|----------|-------|\n| `LC_ALL` | Always set to `C` — affects sort order |\n| `COLUMNS` | Output width (set to `80`) |\n| `TZ` | Timezone (`UTC`) |\n| `TERM` | Terminal type (`xterm-256color`) |\n\n## Output Behavior\n\n- The directory contains 10,000 regular files named `file_00000.dat` …\n  `file_09999.dat` (plus possible variety), all with fixed metadata.\n- Output must match GNU `ls` exactly for each flag — correct name sort\n  (`LC_ALL=C`), correct long-format columns under `-l`, correct size sort under\n  `-S`, and correct column packing under `-C`.\n- **Exit code**: 0 on success, non-zero on error.\n\n## Evaluation\n\nYour implementation is evaluated against a hidden suite of five cases over the\n10k-entry fixture (`no flags`, `-1`, `-l`, `-S`, `-C`). Each case runs your\nbinary and GNU `ls` on the same input and environment and compares output after\ntrailing-whitespace normalization; they must match exactly. **Each of these\ncases has a 60-second per-case timeout** — a correct but pathologically slow\nimplementation that times out scores 0 for that case, so efficient directory\nreading, stat batching, and output buffering matter.\n\n## Time Limit\n\nYou have **2 hours** (7200 seconds) of agent time. Get correctness first on a\nsmaller directory, then ensure the 10k cases complete well within 60s — buffer\nstdout, avoid O(n²) work in sorting/column layout, and minimize per-entry\nsyscalls (only `-l` needs a stat per entry). When ~10 minutes remain, run a\nfinal `cargo build --release`, copy the binary to `/app/workspace/rls`, and make\nsure it runs without crashing.\n\n## Constraints\n\n- You must implement this in **Rust**.\n- You may **not** use the `uutils` crate or any crate that provides a\n  ready-made `ls` implementation.\n- You may use standard library crates and general-purpose crates (e.g. `libc`,\n  `nix`, `clap`).\n- Your final binary must be at `/app/workspace/rls`.\n- The system `ls` command is disabled — do not attempt to call it.\n- Each performance test has a per-case timeout of **60 seconds**.\n\n## Getting Started\n\nExample fixtures are in `/app/workspace/examples/`. Test fixtures are in\n`/app/fixtures/` (the large one is `perf_10k`) and test definitions in\n`/app/tests/`.\n\n## Tips\n\n- **Buffer your output** — wrap stdout in a `BufWriter` and write once; per-line\n  unbuffered writes over 10k entries are a common cause of timeouts.\n- Read the directory once; for non-`-l` modes you do not need to stat each\n  entry, which saves 10k syscalls.\n- Use an efficient sort (the standard library sort is fine); compare names as\n  raw bytes for `LC_ALL=C`.\n- For `-C`, compute the column layout in O(n) per candidate column count, not by\n  re-scanning all entries repeatedly.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":95,"totalLines":95,"truncated":false}},"title":"rust-ls-performance/instruction.md","time":{"start":1781081311544,"end":1781081311715}},"metadata":{"anthropic":{"caller":{"type":"direct"}}},"id":"prt_eb0b8077a001ipb0TxihnkH7NP","sessionID":"ses_14f482c34ffe8du8e4fqDCPwUW","messageID":"msg_eb0b7f7f5001nx0IgdfRuEgxil"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1781081312607,"sessionID":"ses_14f482c34ffe8du8e4fqDCPwUW","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_01BYUU5YjzTAJvouDxxv1DCK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-performance/task.toml"},"output":"<path>/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-performance/task.toml</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: version = \"1.0\"\n2: \n3: [metadata]\n4: difficulty = \"medium\"\n5: category = \"programming\"\n6: tags = [\"rust\", \"ls\", \"coreutils\", \"systems\", \"cli\", \"file-listing\", \"posix\", \"performance\", \"large-dir\"]\n7: \n8: [agent]\n9: timeout_sec = 7200.0\n10: user = \"agent\"\n11: \n12: [verifier]\n13: timeout_sec = 3600.0\n14: \n15: [environment]\n16: build_timeout_sec = 600.0\n17: cpus = 2\n18: memory_mb = 8192\n19: storage_mb = 10240\n20: gpus = 0\n21: allow_internet = false\n22: mcp_servers = []\n23: \n24: [verifier.env]\n25: \n26: [solution.env]\n27: # Injected ONLY into oracle runs. solve.sh writes this token to an oracle marker\n28: # file and test.sh matches it to skip anti-cheat, because the oracle decrypts the\n29: # baked oracle `ls` as its solution. The agent never sees this value, so it cannot\n30: # forge the marker (replaces the old forgeable bare-existence .oracle_solution).\n31: HARBOR_ORACLE_FLAG = \"rustls_perf_bb5ccda623cd1558\"\n\n(End of file - total 31 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"version = \"1.0\"\n\n[metadata]\ndifficulty = \"medium\"\ncategory = \"programming\"\ntags = [\"rust\", \"ls\", \"coreutils\", \"systems\", \"cli\", \"file-listing\", \"posix\", \"performance\", \"large-dir\"]\n\n[agent]\ntimeout_sec = 7200.0\nuser = \"agent\"\n\n[verifier]\ntimeout_sec = 3600.0\n\n[environment]\nbuild_timeout_sec = 600.0\ncpus = 2\nmemory_mb = 8192\nstorage_mb = 10240\ngpus = 0","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/dheeraj/Downloads/refactor/bespoke-labs-tasks-01/rust-ls-performance/task.toml","text":"version = \"1.0\"\n\n[metadata]\ndifficulty = \"medium\"\ncategory = \"programming\"\ntags = [\"rust\", \"ls\", \"coreutils\", \"systems\", \"cli\", \"file-listing\", \"posix\", \"performance\", \"large-dir\"]\n\n[agent]\ntimeout_sec = 7200.0\nuser = \"agent\"\n\n[verifier]\ntimeout_sec = 3600.0\n\n[environment]\nbuild_timeout_sec = 600.0\ncpus = 2\nmemory_mb = 8192\nstorage_mb = 10240\ngpus = 0\nallow_internet = false\nmcp_servers = []\n\n[verifier.env]\n\n[solution.env]\n# Injected ONLY into oracle runs. solve.sh writes this token to an oracle marker\n# file and test.sh matches it to skip anti-cheat, because the oracle decrypts the\n# baked oracle `ls` as its solution. The agent never sees this value, so it cannot\n# forge the marker (replaces the old forgeable bare-existence .oracle_solution).\nHARBOR_ORACLE_FLAG = \"rustls_perf_bb5ccda623cd1558\"","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":31,"totalLines":31,"truncated":false}},"title":"rust-ls-performance/task.toml","time":{"start":1781081312548,"end":1781081312593}},"metadata":{"anthropic":{"caller":{"type":"direct"}}},"id":"prt_eb0b80943001NlpzTROPTGvxTi","sessionID":"ses_14f482c34ffe8du8e4fqDCPwUW","messageID":"msg_eb0b7f7f5001nx0IgdfRuEgxil"}}
